column54: So far it hasn't been the best time At all, the constant worrying on if my partner can be in the room whilst I deliver, the having to attend appointment on my own and it effecting my mental health not to be allowed my partner support with me during difficult times, I'm high risk and suffer from a bleeding disorder and have to go through all this on my own, and have to go back and explain to my partner what I've been told, the negative side effect on our mental health is horrible, Im 33 weeks and never once seen the midwife I am suppose to see I have no idea what going on with that. I've been passes between 2 other midwifes in my unit. I was told there's a high chance I'd be put to sleep under general anaesthetic and at the moment not know what will be happening with the baby once he's here, not having my partner in the ward once he's delivered yet its his son and has all the same rights I have, how the hospital are restricting visits from the fathers  is appalling. I myself are under Bangor hospital and I find it shocking to be told my partner isn't allowed to be there after the birth or during any of my appointments. Being pregnant it's self is scary but at the moment it's severely stressful and emotional time which is not good for baby yet the hospitals do not care in the slightest...  Fathers of the baby should have the right to support there partners and be there every step of the way...

column54: Absolutely terrible. First time pregnancy and I feel so alone. My partner hasn't been able to attend any scans or appointments. I have had to go into hospital twice for bleeding and once for reduced movement and I've had to do that alone, I suffer from anxiety anyway and I'm off my meds due to pregnancy and during those situations I should be able to have my support of my partner as should anyone. Thankfully all was okay but it may not have been and to go through that alone is unacceptable. I also suffer from long term chronic back pain and have been fobbed off throughout resulting in incredibly painful seizures. During these seizures I've been unable to contact my midwife and advice given afterwards was different contacts, when I tried those on another occasion I was asked what do I want to do?! I am ringing for their help and advice and none was given so me and my partner have had to deal with it alone. I haven't been able to attend any antenatal classes in person and it's only now there is a good variety of free ones online. I have managed to find some but no help from local midwives just my own research. Appalling treatment for someone who should be relishing in celebration.

column54:
It is far from ideal, my partner not being able to come to scans with me was particularly unpleasant. 

This is my third pregnancy, if it had been my first it would have been particularly joyless, but I donåt feel as awful as itås my final pregnancy so I know what to expect. 

Home schooling my oldest child and having no access to nursery while having morning sickness and working from home is a memory I would rather forget. As a slight bonus I saved some money towards mat leave from nursery fees. 

I feel massively less healthy in this pregnancy than my others due to lack of access to exercise facilities and working from home means moving less than when Iåm in the office. 

It is very anxiety provoking ahead of the birth, especially as rates are high and one of my daughters bubbles recently closed due to a positive case.

On the whole the midwives looking after me have been brilliant. I really like the change of system where previously you would see your GP first, but now you can contact the Midwifery help line directly. This is great and perfect for working women.
My only complaint has been when I went in to the local hospital day unit. They were not wearing masks in the middle of the pandemic, complaining about their manager, and appeared to generally not want to be at work. Such a shame, as they often work with some of the most anxious and concerned mothers who are referred there due to an issue.

column54:
I had a TFMR in August 2020 at 21 weeks. ( all tests took so long because of the pandemic and I had to go all the way to London for the termination because they would t do it in Wales) the wait was horrendous and I had absolutely NO after care. 

We then tried again 6/7 months later and I insisted that I had a NIPT assessment done as soon as possible.. this was done at 9/10 weeks.( This should be offered to every mum and shouldnåt be an optional test after a high risk is presented around 14/15 weeks at the quad testing. )

I am now 36 week and am due early December, winter! Plus Covid! Plus Christmas month. A lot of risk again. So I am hoping for the best birth experience possible but setting my expectations bar to low. 

I find the current methods of carrying my own pregnancy file very old fashioned and totally out of date. What if that got lost??? Is there an easy accessible paperless option? Would also have to save me repeating myself at every appointment that is my Second Pregnancy- first baby. This breaks my heart every time. So no when an appointment to see baby is doing well and growing as he should I also leave with grief of my lost baby. Itås never a nice experience.

Which I was reassured by as I had some concerns over a new vaccine that hasnåt been tested on pregnant women anyway, as medical professionals donåt always get things right - e.g Thalidomide. Guidance then changed - information was all encouraging pregnant women to have the vaccine backed with info that itås safe and wonåt cause any problems for your pregnancy etc. I was never worried about it causing problems in pregnancy , I was worried about the unknown, potentially longer term effects, on a growing unborn fetus, and that was never really addressed in articles, as not enough time has passed to measure that. Itås only now, 9 months after a lot of women started getting the vaccine, that the effects can be measured, and it looks like everything is fine. Which is great. But imagine if it wasnåt, and you are personally responsible for having made that decision.

column54:
I went into this pregnancy totally disillusioned. I was not prepared for many of my symptoms (early cramping for 2 weeks, extreme fatigue etc). I would not say I enjoy being pregnant and I would like time to fly and for the baby to be born. I hear wonderful stories about people enjoying being pregnant but I've generally been uncomfortable, anxious and tired. 

I feel that there is definitely not enough support for pregnant women during the first 12 weeks of pregnancy. I was extremely frightened at the pain I was feeling and the doctors/midwives kept telling me they were unable to help until I was at a certain stage in the pregnancy. I felt very abandoned and unsupported.

I did have to go to the EPU at week 9 and I have no negative things to say about this department. They took me seriously and listened to my worries and were extremely happy to be able to give me good news (which is not always the case for them). I am also very happy now that my midwives are able to support me - I have two wonderful midwives who are kind and supportive. I just wish that they could have been assigned to me when I most needed it.

I have also had mixed experiences during scans/consultant appointments. My 12 week scan was carried out by a lady that I felt was very cold and did not explain what was happening. My first consultant appointment left me in tears and very frightened and fat shamed without giving me proper information or advice other than to diet (which I believed was not what I was meant to do while pregnant) - and it turned out I was under the wrong consultant anyway after I burst into tears at reception and was helped by a wonderful midwife. My 20 week scan was carried out by two lovely, very kind and informative women and made me feel very at ease. My next consultant appointment was with a male doctor who was very kind and supportive and made me feel very reassured. My follow up 20 week scan was carried out by the same lady as the 12 week scan and the baby was in the wrong position but she kept huffing and puffing and made me feel like it was my fault.

column73: Between 12-20 weeks I was advised by midwives that they are not accessible to me and have to go through gp. I understand that this has been in place for some time but it makes no sense as we are pregnant during that time and they can do things to support your pregnancy. It feels as those they donåt bother in case you miscarry and thereås nothing they can do anyway which is pretty poor. I was referred to prams due to severe anxiety which is now worse due to threat of early labour and the earliest they can see me in March despite feeling suicidal at the thought of anything bad happening to my baby. I am currently admitted to singleton due to tightenings and positive test showing I will go into labour. They have explained these can be inaccurate however I have had conflicting information in the last 24 hours. One midwife said Iåd have scans and be here at least 48 hours as they would expect labour to happen within first two days of the test, the consultant said happy to let me go today even though Iåm still having tightenings. I will stay for 48 hours but makes it so hard doing the right thing. I was also put on a ward with two women in labour while trying to prevent mine which was completely distressing. Other than that singleton have been a huge support when no other services were willing to be, particularly EPU who recognised my anxiety and even arranged a reassurance scan for me.

column54:
I have felt guilty and useless as pregnancy has prevented me from working in my usual patient facing role while my colleagues had to face the challenges of covid-19 head on. I have, however, been grateful to my work and the NHS for protecting me. I have missed sharing my pregnancy journey with friends and colleagues. 
Midwives are doing their best with limitations that realistically are necessary. For the most part, the care has been good. I feel like my care has generally been very hands off, but I question whether this would have been any different pre covid anyway - my understanding of UK antenatal care is very much a hands off approach that becomes less so as you progress, with midwives available if you have concerns (or for those less than 20 weeks, you may be required to attend a&e).

Fathers of the baby should have the right to support there partners and be there every step of the way...

It is far from ideal, my partner not being able to come to scans with me was particularly unpleasant. 

This is my third pregnancy, if it had been my first it would have been particularly joyless, but I donåt feel as awful as itås my final pregnancy so I know what to expect. 

Home schooling my oldest child and having no access to nursery while having morning sickness and working from home is a memory I would rather forget. As a slight bonus I saved some money towards mat leave from nursery fees. 

I feel massively less healthy in this pregnancy than my others due to lack of access to exercise facilities and working from home means moving less than when Iåm in the office. 

It is very anxiety provoking ahead of the birth, especially as rates are high and one of my daughters bubbles recently closed due to a positive case.

Overall I did not feel very supported, my initial appointment was over the phone due to covid and was just a rushed blur of information like points being checked off a list. Due to a previous miscarriage I was very worried about this pregnancy and felt I didnåt get a lot of support or reassurance. 
Then throughout my other midwife appointments which were in person at my drs surgery I kept having different midwives due to shortages and changes within the health board so I was hard to establish a relationship where I felt supported. I had to attended All my appointments alone as my husband was not allowed into the buildings and had to wait in the car. He was allowed the attend my 12 and 20 week scans but only for the duration of the scan and then asked to leave the premises. 
There were no nhs antenatal classes being run in person and oneås set up online weåre sporadic and usually booked up. 
I did not know any midwives during my birth and saw probably about 6 different ones at the hospital while in labour.

Everything was by myself due to covid restrictions in our hospital do baby's Dad was there for an hour during his birth & that was it. He wasn't even allowed in to help me out to the car with baby & all our bags, I was left to struggle. I was home an hour & got a phonecall asking me to go to the midwife the morning after (I had stitches and was struggling to move due to them) but I had to go alone with baby.
